His talents gained him admission to the literary euque, known as the Sci- pionic circle, the fashionable representatives of the new Hellenic culture. Scipio Aemilianus was the centre of the coterie‚ which included Laelius and Furius Philo, Sulpicius Gallus, Q. Fabius Labeo, M. Popillius, the philosopher Pa- naetius, and the historian Polybius. These being rnen of educa- tion and taste, unreservedly recognised the immeasurable superi- ority of Greek literature as compared with the rude efforts of their native writers. To present to a Roman audience a faithful reproduction of the best Hellenic models, in pure and polished Latin, seemed to thern the ideal of literary excellence. Style was inore valued than strength, correctness of form more than originality of thought. Such was the literary atmosphere which Terence breathed ς and his enemies‚ not confining themselves to gross aspersions on his moral character, openly affirmed that the plays produced under his name were really the work of his dis- tinguished patrons.
